# The Bug

The function initializes `max = 0`, which fails when the array contains **only negative numbers**. In that case, `0` is greater than every element, so the function incorrectly returns `0` instead of the actual largest (least negative) number.

**Example failure:**
```javascript
findMax([-5, -2, -8, -1]); // returns 0, should return -1
```

# The Fix

Initialize `max` with the first element of the array instead of `0`:

```javascript
function findMax(arr) {
  if (arr.length === 0) return undefined; // handle empty arrays

  let max = arr[0];
  for (let i = 1; i < arr.length; i++) {
    if (arr[i] > max) max = arr[i];
  }
  return max;
}
```

# Why This Works

- `max` now starts as an actual element from the array, so the comparison is always between real values.
- The loop starts at index `1` since `arr[0]` is already the initial `max`.
- The empty-array guard prevents `undefined` behavior when `arr[0]` doesn't exist.

# Alternative One-Liner

If your environment supports it, you can use the spread operator with `Math.max`:

```javascript
function findMax(arr) {
  return Math.max(...arr);
}
```

This works correctly for negative numbers, positive numbers, and mixed values.

